"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkmy_website=globalThis.webpackChunkmy_website||[]).push([[8130],{77735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/2026/04/24/nodejs-eventloop-mg1-simulator","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2026/04/24/nodejs-eventloop-mg1-simulator","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-24/nodejs-eventloop-mg1-simulator.mdx","title":"Why Your p99 Latency Destroys Node.js Event Loop Throughput","description":"An interactive M/G/1 queue simulator that shows why a slow tail latency wrecks throughput \u2014 and what the event loop cost really looks like.","date":"2026-04-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"nodejs","permalink":"/blog/tags/nodejs"},{"inline":true,"label":"eventloop","permalink":"/blog/tags/eventloop"},{"inline":true,"label":"performance","permalink":"/blog/tags/performance"},{"inline":true,"label":"queuing-theory","permalink":"/blog/tags/queuing-theory"},{"inline":true,"label":"mg1","permalink":"/blog/tags/mg-1"}],"readingTime":3.78,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Why Your p99 Latency Destroys Node.js Event Loop Throughput","description":"An interactive M/G/1 queue simulator that shows why a slow tail latency wrecks throughput \u2014 and what the event loop cost really looks like.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["nodejs","eventloop","performance","queuing-theory","mg1"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Bitmaps for Access Control: Scaling Notification Fan-Out with Redis ACL Checks","permalink":"/blog/2025/04/06/data-structures-applicability-1"}},"content":"import Mg1Simulator from \'@site/src/components/Mg1Simulator\';\\n\\nEveryone is tired of listening \\"Node.js runs on a single event loop\\" and related blogposts. I am aware of it.\\n\\n_\\"One slow task blocking that loop means every other request waits.\\"_\\n\\nEngineers know this, but knowing is different from understanding and seeing in action.\\n\\nThis post is an interactive playground: tweak arrival rate and latency distribution, and watch what happens to queue depth and response time. The simulation runs entirely in your browser via a Web Worker.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## The model\\n\\nA single event loop is a single-server queue. Requests arrive, get processed one at a time, and every arriving request that finds the server busy joins the queue.\\n\\nThis is the classic **M/G/1 queue**:\\n\\n- **M** \u2014 arrivals are Markovian (Poisson/exponential inter-arrival)\\n- **G** \u2014 service times follow a *general* distribution\\n- **1** \u2014 one server (the event loop thread)\\n\\nFor an M/G/1 queue, the [Pollaczek\u2013Khinchine formula](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pollaczek%E2%80%93Khinchine_formula) gives the expected waiting time:\\n\\n$$\\nW_q = \\\\frac{\\\\lambda \\\\cdot E[S^2]}{2 \\\\cdot (1 - \\\\rho)}\\n$$\\n\\nWhere:\\n\\n- $\\\\lambda$ = arrival rate (requests per second)\\n- $E[S]$ = mean service time\\n- $E[S^2]$ = second moment of service time (variance + mean\xb2)\\n- $\\\\rho = \\\\lambda \\\\cdot E[S]$ = utilization (must be < 1 for stability)\\n\\nThe key insight: waiting time depends not just on average service time, but on $E[S^2]$ \u2014 the variance. A long tail (high p99 relative to p50) blows up $E[S^2]$ and sends wait times skyrocketing even at moderate utilization.\\n\\n## Try it yourself\\n\\nSet your arrival rate in RPS and your latency distribution in milliseconds. The simulator uses piecewise-linear interpolation between your chosen percentiles, then falls off exponentially in the tail beyond p99.\\nTry switching these parameters and then compare to the NodeJS version [here](https://github.com/lukas8219/blogpost-examples/blob/57f4d75a39576c8a4760c81e04c02293916b884f/mg1-eventloop-sim.js)!\\n- 100 RPS at 30 seconds\\n- 130 RPS at 30 seconds\\n- 150 RPS to 150 at 30 seconds\\n- 200 RPS to 300 at 30 seconds\\n\\nYou will understand in the next section!\\n\\n<Mg1Simulator />\\n\\n## What to notice\\n\\n### 1. The hidden tax of variance\\n\\nTwo latency distributions can have similar means _(p75)_ but wildly different mean service time and queueing behavior.\\n\\n| Scenario | p50 | p75 | p95 | p99 | Mean service |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| A | 2 ms | 3 ms | 5 ms | 8 ms | ~3.2 ms |\\n| B | 2 ms | 5 ms | 20 ms | 50 ms | ~5.6 ms |\\n\\nScenario B is what happens when a database hiccups, a downstream service flakes, or a CPU-bound task sneaks into the event loop. Even though the *median* is the same, the heavier tail means $E[S^2]$ is much larger \u2014 and the queueing penalty explodes.\\n\\n### 2. The \u03c1 \u2192 1 wall\\n\\nAt 100 RPS, $\\\\rho < 0.6$, queueing delays are modest. You might not notice the event loop constraint at all.\\n\\nAt roughly 130 RPS, $\\\\rho = 0.8$, things get spicy. The tail of the response time distribution stretches out.\\n\\nAt 150 RPS, $\\\\rho = 0.95$, the queue is almost never empty. One slow request kicks off a backlog that takes many fast requests to drain.\\n\\nAt 200 RPS above with $\\\\rho \\\\geq 1$, the queue grows without bound. The theoretical mean wait becomes infinite. In practice, memory runs out or requests time out first.\\n\\n### 3. Why this matters for Node.js\\n\\nIn Node.js, that \\"queue\\" is the event loop itself. There is no separate thread pool handling your synchronous JavaScript \u2014 just one loop.\\n\\nA single 50 ms blocking call at the wrong moment forces every other callback, timer, and I/O completion to wait. The p99 latency of *your* service becomes the p99 of the *worst* thing currently running, plus whatever queue has built up behind it.\\n\\nThat is why `setTimeout(fn, 0)` and `process.nextTick` do not help when the loop itself is the bottleneck. They just reshuffle the same queue.\\n\\n## Takeaways\\n\\n- **Monitor event loop lag**, not just endpoint latency. A healthy service can have terrible loop lag.\\n- **Treat high-variance tasks as a capacity problem**. Even if they are rare, they determine your queueing penalty through $E[S^2]$.\\n- **Offload CPU work** to worker threads, child processes, or other services. Keep the event loop for I/O coordination.\\n- **Set latency objectives at p99 or p999**, not just average. The tail is what breaks you under load.\\n- **M/G/1** does not punish only $E[S]$ (mean). It punishes at $E[S^2]$ (p99 variance to p50).\\n\\nFeel free to play with the numbers above. Find the $\\\\rho$ where your setup transitions from \\"fine\\" to \\"on fire.\\" That is your real operating limit."},{"id":"/2025/04/06/data-structures-applicability-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2025/04/06/data-structures-applicability-1","source":"@site/blog/2025-04-06/data-structures-applicability-1.mdx","title":"Bitmaps for Access Control: Scaling Notification Fan-Out with Redis ACL Checks","description":"Why bitmaps are an efficient way to do access-control checks for high-volume real-time notifications, and when to use them.","date":"2025-04-06T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"notifications","permalink":"/blog/tags/notifications"},{"inline":true,"label":"datastructures","permalink":"/blog/tags/datastructures"},{"inline":true,"label":"bitmaps","permalink":"/blog/tags/bitmaps"},{"inline":true,"label":"redis","permalink":"/blog/tags/redis"}],"readingTime":4.98,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Bitmaps for Access Control: Scaling Notification Fan-Out with Redis ACL Checks","description":"Why bitmaps are an efficient way to do access-control checks for high-volume real-time notifications, and when to use them.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["notifications","datastructures","bitmaps","redis"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why Your p99 Latency Destroys Node.js Event Loop Throughput","permalink":"/blog/2026/04/24/nodejs-eventloop-mg1-simulator"},"nextItem":{"title":"The Tale of How We Paid Back Years of Tech Debt in a Month","permalink":"/blog/2025/03/31/network-bandwidth-reduction"}},"content":"Most engineers spend most of their time with familiar data structures: arrays, queues, sets, and maps.\\n\\nThat makes sense. They solve everyday problems well.\\n\\nBitmaps are different. They feel lower-level, more specialized, and easy to ignore.\\n\\nThat is a mistake, because in the right problem they are extremely effective.\\n\\nThis post is about one of those problems: using bitmaps to route real-time notifications without hitting the database on every message.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## The problem\\n\\nIn many SaaS systems, access control is built on many-to-many relationships.\\n\\nImagine something Slack-like with one more layer of permissioning.\\n\\nYou have:\\n\\n- users `U`\\n- groups `G`\\n- teams `T`\\n\\nAnd the rules look like this:\\n\\n- a user belongs to one or more groups\\n- a group can access one or more teams\\n- a message sent to a team should only reach users who are allowed to see that team\\n\\nThat creates a routing problem.\\n\\nEvery notification must reach only the correct online recipients, even when multiple permission paths exist.\\n\\n## When the obvious solution stops being cheap\\n\\nFor a long time, normal database queries may be enough. With the right indexes, that can work well.\\n\\nThe more interesting case is what happens when the system starts handling tens of thousands of notifications per second.\\n\\nAt that point, asking the database the same access-control question over and over gets expensive. Even if each query is acceptable on its own, the total cost starts to show up in latency, CPU, memory pressure, and infrastructure size.\\n\\nThat is where a different representation helps.\\n\\n### How to know if you have this problem\\n\\nConsider bitmaps when:\\n\\n- the same access query runs on every notification\\n- the query result changes infrequently compared to how often it is asked\\n- user ids can be mapped to dense numeric indexes\\n- you need sub-millisecond routing decisions\\n\\n## Why bitmaps fit this problem\\n\\nA bitmap is compact and optimized for binary state.\\n\\nThat makes it a good fit for questions like:\\n\\n- does this user have access to this team?\\n- is this user online right now?\\n- which users satisfy both conditions?\\n\\nThese are yes-or-no questions, and that is where bitmaps shine.\\n\\n## The design\\n\\nFor each tenant, you can represent both access and presence with Redis bitmaps:\\n\\n```text\\nteams:<tenantId>:<teamId>\\nonline-users:<tenantId>\\n```\\n\\nEach bit position maps to a stable numeric user index. In some systems that can be the raw user id. In others it is a separate dense mapping.\\n\\n- in `teams:<tenantId>:<teamId>`, bit `1` means that user can access the team\\n- in `online-users:<tenantId>`, bit `1` means that user is currently online\\n\\nThis assumes the relationship has already been denormalized into a read-optimized format.\\n\\nInstead of querying relational state for every notification, you can move the hot routing step into Redis.\\n\\n## Example\\n\\nA relational version might look like this:\\n\\n```sql\\nSELECT\\n  ug.user\\nFROM\\n  groups ug\\nWHERE\\n  ug.teams IN (<list of teams>)\\n  AND ug.tenantId = <tenantId>\\n```\\n\\nWith bitmaps, the same routing step can be done with bitmap operations.\\n\\nHere is a simplified Lua example:\\n\\n```lua\\nlocal tenantId = ARGV[1]\\nlocal tmp_or_key = \'tmp:teams:\' .. tenantId\\nlocal notify_key = \'tmp:notification:\' .. tenantId\\nlocal online_key = \'online-users:\' .. tenantId\\n\\nredis.call(\'BITOP\', \'OR\', tmp_or_key, unpack(KEYS))\\nredis.call(\'BITOP\', \'AND\', notify_key, tmp_or_key, online_key)\\n\\nlocal max_index = redis.call(\'STRLEN\', notify_key) * 8\\nlocal notified_users = {}\\nfor i = 0, max_index - 1 do\\n  local bit = redis.call(\'GETBIT\', notify_key, i)\\n  if bit == 1 then\\n    table.insert(notified_users, i)\\n  end\\nend\\n\\nredis.call(\'DEL\', tmp_or_key)\\nredis.call(\'DEL\', notify_key)\\n\\nreturn notified_users\\n```\\n\\nThis script is meant to explain the idea, not to claim that bit-by-bit scanning is always the best extraction strategy for large bitmaps.\\n\\nWhat happens here is simple:\\n\\n1. combine all target team bitmaps with `OR`\\n2. intersect that result with the online-users bitmap using `AND`\\n3. the remaining set bits are users who both have access and are online\\n\\nSo the routing decision becomes a few in-memory bitmap operations instead of another database query on the hot path.\\n\\n## Why this can be faster\\n\\nBefore this kind of optimization, every notification could trigger another database read, with all the usual overhead: parsing, planning, execution, buffer checks, and sometimes disk access.\\n\\nUnder sustained fan-out load, that gets expensive.\\n\\nWith bitmaps, the hot path becomes a set of in-memory operations on compact structures. That usually means:\\n\\n- lower latency\\n- more predictable routing cost\\n- less repetitive read pressure on the database\\n- more room for the database to focus on writes and less cacheable queries\\n\\n## Trade-offs\\n\\nThis approach is not free.\\n\\nYou need:\\n\\n- dense numeric identifiers, or at least a stable mapping to bitmap positions\\n- update flows that keep access and online-state bitmaps current\\n- enough confidence that the read amplification you are avoiding is worth the write-side bookkeeping\\n\\nAnd if cardinality grows far enough, it is worth studying [Roaring Bitmaps](https://roaringbitmap.org/) as a more space-efficient representation.\\n\\n### Practical sizing\\n\\nIf you have 100,000 users, a single bitmap is about 12.5 KB. If you have 1,000 teams, that is roughly 12.5 MB of bitmap data per tenant. Redis handles that easily. But if you have millions of users and tens of thousands of teams, Roaring Bitmaps become worth evaluating.\\n\\n## Takeaways\\n\\n1. Could you do something similar with normal `Set`s? Yes, but memory footprint and operation cost often look worse.\\n2. Bitmaps are great when the problem reduces to yes-or-no membership checks.\\n3. They are especially useful when the same access-control question is asked at very high frequency.\\n4. Redis can be an efficient routing engine when you model the state in a form it can process cheaply.\\n\\nBitmaps are not a general-purpose answer to every permission problem.\\n\\nBut for ACL-heavy notification fan-out, they can be a very sharp tool.\\n\\n### Quick evaluation\\n\\nBefore adopting bitmaps for ACL, verify:\\n\\n- [ ] Your user ids can be mapped to dense numeric indexes\\n- [ ] Team membership changes are infrequent compared to notification volume\\n- [ ] You have a way to keep online-state bitmaps current\\n- [ ] Your total bitmap size per tenant fits comfortably in memory"},{"id":"/2025/03/31/network-bandwidth-reduction","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2025/03/31/network-bandwidth-reduction","source":"@site/blog/2025-03-31/network-bandwidth-reduction.mdx","title":"The Tale of How We Paid Back Years of Tech Debt in a Month","description":"How an oversized IAM session object caused cascading infrastructure problems, and why trimming hot-path data models often beats scaling.","date":"2025-03-31T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"redis","permalink":"/blog/tags/redis"},{"inline":true,"label":"bandwidth","permalink":"/blog/tags/bandwidth"},{"inline":true,"label":"cost","permalink":"/blog/tags/cost"}],"readingTime":4.64,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"The Tale of How We Paid Back Years of Tech Debt in a Month","description":"How an oversized IAM session object caused cascading infrastructure problems, and why trimming hot-path data models often beats scaling.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["redis","bandwidth","cost"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Bitmaps for Access Control: Scaling Notification Fan-Out with Redis ACL Checks","permalink":"/blog/2025/04/06/data-structures-applicability-1"},"nextItem":{"title":"Open Source Tales #1: WebSocket Operator","permalink":"/blog/2025/03/31/open-source-tales-1"}},"content":"Back in 2022 - while I was at Luma Health - we went through a major outage that cost hours of downtime, a lot of engineering effort, and a fair amount of customer frustration.\\n\\nOne painful discovery from that period was this: we had modeled an internal IAM session object very poorly.\\n\\nThat mistake stayed quiet for a long time. As the company grew, it stopped being quiet.\\n\\nThis post is about how a single data-modeling decision created years of infrastructure debt, and why fixing it took a month but paid for itself immediately.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## Why this mattered\\n\\nIn healthcare software, access-control state is core system data. Systems that handle Patient Health Information need to enforce those boundaries consistently across backend flows.\\n\\nOur `session` object carried the data needed for that enforcement: token, settings, groups, facilities, and other metadata required to authorize work.\\n\\nThe problem was not the existence of the session.\\nThe problem was its size.\\n\\n## The modeling mistake\\n\\nAt some point, we chose the convenient path: load full `groups` and `facilities` data into the session JSON and cache it.\\n\\nThat worked until larger customers arrived with more complex account structures.\\n\\nEventually we had session payloads reaching **2.6 MB**.\\n\\nThat is not a small piece of authorization context anymore.\\n\\nIn several job-processing paths, services fetched the cached session repeatedly as work moved through the platform. Sometimes that happened dozens of times for the same logical flow. Our system averaged around 2,000 jobs per second and could spike much higher.\\n\\nAt that point, the issue was no longer just wasteful serialization. It had become steady network pressure between services and the cache layer.\\n\\n## What the impact looked like\\n\\nThat oversized payload showed up everywhere:\\n\\n- unstable and slower HTTP APIs\\n\\n![rest-latencies](/assets/rest-latencies.webp)\\n\\n\\n- oversized cache infrastructure\\n- higher service-to-cache bandwidth consumption\\n- pressure that forced architectural band-aids into the system\\n\\n![busy-monday-pre](/assets/busy-monday-pre.webp)\\n\\nWe even introduced supporting components and patterns just to reduce the blast radius:\\n\\n- a dedicated `pubsub-service` to offload slow event-loops/slow publishes\\n- a `jobless` pattern where only job identifiers were published and the body was fetched elsewhere\\n\\nThose were symptoms of the same underlying problem: too much data moving through the hot path.\\n\\n### How to spot this in your own system\\n\\nIf you suspect a similar problem:\\n\\n1. Check the size of your most frequently cached objects.\\n2. Multiply that size by how many times they are fetched per request.\\n3. Multiply again by your request rate.\\n4. If the result is in the gigabits per second range, your object model is likely too heavy for the hot path.\\n5. Have Bandwidth alarms for Redis. Usually, it should not go over 70%.\\n\\n## The fix\\n\\nThe actual code change was small compared to the impact.\\n\\nInstead of loading full group documents while building the session, we introduced a feature-flagged path that selected only the fields needed in the hot path. In simplified form, the idea looked like this:\\n\\n```javascript\\nQuery.select(\'_id\')\\n```\\n\\nThat snippet is only illustrative. The important part is that we stopped materializing large relationship payloads into the session when the hot path only needed compact identifiers.\\n\\nThat was enough to build a much smaller session object without changing the higher-level authorization model.\\n\\nOf course, the hard part was not writing the line.\\nThe hard part was rolling it out safely.\\n\\n## Why rollout took time\\n\\nSession shape was deeply embedded across many services and internal libraries, so we had to treat this as a compatibility project rather than a simple refactor.\\n\\nThat meant:\\n\\n- auditing service and library versions\\n- searching the codebase for assumptions about session shape\\n- using feature flags per tenant\\n- monitoring product and platform metrics during rollout\\n\\nThe questions were practical and unsettling:\\n\\n- would messages stop being sent?\\n- would notifications silently disappear?\\n- would some customer workflows degrade in ways we would only discover later?\\n\\nSo we rolled it carefully.\\n\\n## Outcome\\n\\nThe rollout took nearly a month across around 90 backend services, followed by tenant-by-tenant enablement.\\n\\nThe results justified the caution:\\n\\n- roughly 60% reduction in the relevant cache-related network traffic\\n- much more stable API latencies\\n- clear room to downsize parts of the REST layer\\n- near-elimination of the network pressure created by our temporary band-aids\\n\\nJust as important, we were finally able to start removing workarounds that should never have become architecture in the first place.\\n\\n![busy-monday-after-rollout](/assets/busy-monday-after-rollout.webp)\\n\\n## The deeper lesson\\n\\nThe expensive part of technical debt is often not the original bug. It is the ecosystem of compensating decisions that grows around it.\\n\\nOne oversized payload led to:\\n\\n- bigger infrastructure\\n- extra services\\n- more complicated publish paths\\n- more operational anxiety\\n\\nAll of that because a hot-path object carried far more data than it needed.\\n\\n### When to consider this kind of optimization\\n\\nNot every large cached object needs fixing. Consider trimming hot-path payloads when:\\n\\n- the object is fetched multiple times per workflow\\n- the fetch rate scales with traffic volume\\n- the object contains data that is only needed in a small fraction of use cases\\n- you have already scaled infrastructure and the problem persists\\n\\n## Takeaway\\n\\nThere is a lot of justified attention on product features, growth, and customer-facing delivery.\\n\\nBut backend modeling decisions matter just as much when the system starts to scale.\\n\\nSometimes the best optimization is not a fancy algorithm. It is revisiting a data model that quietly became too expensive for the path it lives on.\\n\\nAnd sometimes one month of careful cleanup pays back years of architectural interest."},{"id":"/2025/03/31/open-source-tales-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2025/03/31/open-source-tales-1","source":"@site/blog/2025-03-31/open-source-tales-1.mdx","title":"Open Source Tales #1: WebSocket Operator","description":"How I turned an old scaling problem into an open source experiment, and why platform-native routing beats application-level workarounds for stateful systems.","date":"2025-03-31T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"websocket","permalink":"/blog/tags/websocket"}],"readingTime":4.22,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Open Source Tales #1: WebSocket Operator","description":"How I turned an old scaling problem into an open source experiment, and why platform-native routing beats application-level workarounds for stateful systems.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["websocket"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"The Tale of How We Paid Back Years of Tech Debt in a Month","permalink":"/blog/2025/03/31/network-bandwidth-reduction"},"nextItem":{"title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Data Reference","permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference"}},"content":"One of the most interesting problems I have worked on was something that is easy in stateless systems and much less pleasant in stateful ones: scaling WebSocket servers horizontally.\\n\\nIf your application keeps connection state in memory, adding more replicas is not enough. You also need a way to route a message to the replica that owns the target connection.\\n\\nThat was the real problem.\\n\\nThis post is about why application-level messaging workarounds eventually fail, and what a platform-native alternative looks like.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## The constraints\\n\\nOur original environment came with a long list of restrictions:\\n\\n- we had to respect an internal framework built around model events\\n- IAM filtering had to be preserved\\n- Socket.IO was already part of the stack\\n- RabbitMQ-based Socket.IO plugins were considered too costly\\n- Redis plugins were not a good fit for our case\\n- multi-tab support was required\\n- we wanted to avoid adding new infrastructure if possible\\n\\nIn other words, this was not a clean-sheet design.\\n\\nOur WebSocket servers also ran on older Socket.IO versions and barely used the framework\'s stronger features. At that point, they could almost have been plain WebSocket servers.\\n\\n## The first solution\\n\\nTo scale horizontally, we used Redis Pub/Sub so WebSocket servers could forward messages to each other.\\n\\nThat solved the immediate routing problem, but it also made me realize something important: scaling a stateful WebSocket layer is itself a costly architectural choice.\\n\\nOnce you go down that path, you inherit a set of distributed-systems problems whether you wanted them or not.\\n\\n## The uncomfortable lessons\\n\\nThe pain points were familiar:\\n\\n- observability became harder\\n- Redis Pub/Sub introduced delivery and bandwidth concerns\\n- connection distribution across replicas was weak\\n- some replicas ran hot while others stayed cold\\n\\nAt some point I started thinking the real question was not \\"how do I scale this with Redis?\\" but \\"what if the platform should help route and rebalance connections?\\"\\n\\nKubernetes, proxies, sidecars, and service discovery started to look more interesting than another application-level messaging layer.\\n\\n## The project idea\\n\\nA couple of years later I found [this article](https://medium.com/lumen-engineering-blog/how-to-implement-a-distributed-and-auto-scalable-websocket-server-architecture-on-kubernetes-4cc32e1dfa45), which described a Kubernetes-based approach to distributed WebSocket routing.\\n\\nThat article was the spark. I had already solved a similar problem under stricter constraints, and they had solved it in a cleaner infrastructure-aware way. That made me wonder how many teams were independently reinventing roughly the same architecture.\\n\\nThat curiosity became [websocket-operator](https://github.com/lukas8219/websocket-operator).\\n\\n## What the operator does\\n\\nThe project is a blueprint for running horizontally scalable WebSocket workloads on Kubernetes without depending on the older Redis Pub/Sub shape of the solution I had used before.\\n\\nThe central idea is simple: route connections and messages through Kubernetes-aware components instead of pushing the whole problem into a broker plugin.\\n\\nThe operator currently revolves around three components.\\n\\n### Load balancer\\n\\nThis is the user-facing entrypoint.\\n\\nIt accepts connections and routes them toward proxy sidecars using the same connection-placement logic shared elsewhere in the system.\\n\\n### Proxy sidecar\\n\\nThe sidecar intercepts WebSocket traffic and can proxy a message to another sidecar that actually owns the destination connection.\\n\\nThis is what lets the system route stateful traffic across replicas.\\n\\n### Controller\\n\\nThe controller injects sidecars into workloads marked with the `ws.operator/enabled` label and manages the Kubernetes-side control loop around that setup.\\n\\nThe longer-term goal is to help with behaviors such as rebalancing, but that part is still project direction, not a claim that every piece is already production-complete.\\n\\n## Why this interested me\\n\\nThis project let me combine two things I wanted at the same time:\\n\\n- deeper Go and Kubernetes operator work\\n- a chance to revisit an old distributed-systems problem without the original constraints\\n\\nThat made it more than a coding exercise. It was a way to pressure-test a better architectural direction.\\n\\n## Roadmap\\n\\nThe roadmap is still intentionally practical:\\n\\n- pluggable hashing strategies for connection routing\\n- pluggable message-routing logic\\n- support for broadcast-style delivery\\n\\nThe first versions assume JSON messages, but there is no good reason to stop there. Real systems may want binary payloads, text frames, or custom protocols.\\n\\n## Should you scale your WebSocket layer?\\n\\nBefore building anything like this, ask yourself:\\n\\n- [ ] Is connection count actually the bottleneck, or is it business logic?\\n- [ ] Can you vertically scale your current instances instead?\\n- [ ] Is your WebSocket traffic evenly distributed, or bursty?\\n- [ ] Do you have a Kubernetes-native platform to lean on?\\n\\nIf your answers suggest that horizontal scaling is truly necessary, then an operator-based approach is worth exploring. If not, you may be solving the wrong problem.\\n\\n## Takeaway\\n\\nStateful systems become expensive in ways stateless systems do not. Before scaling a WebSocket architecture, make sure the product really needs it.\\n\\nIf it does, lean on the platform where possible instead of pushing every routing problem into application code.\\n\\nSometimes the right lesson from a past system is not how to rebuild it.\\nSometimes it is how to avoid rebuilding the same constraints."},{"id":"/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference","source":"@site/blog/2024-03-15/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference.mdx","title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Data Reference","description":"Why Redis should store coordination data, not full payloads, and how we redesigned our delayed-job system around that principle.","date":"2024-03-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"delayed-jobs","permalink":"/blog/tags/delayed-jobs"},{"inline":true,"label":"redis","permalink":"/blog/tags/redis"},{"inline":true,"label":"distributed-systems","permalink":"/blog/tags/distributed-systems"},{"inline":true,"label":"readisismorethanacache","permalink":"/blog/tags/readisismorethanacache"}],"readingTime":5.49,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Data Reference","description":"Why Redis should store coordination data, not full payloads, and how we redesigned our delayed-job system around that principle.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["delayed-jobs","redis","distributed-systems","readisismorethanacache"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Open Source Tales #1: WebSocket Operator","permalink":"/blog/2025/03/31/open-source-tales-1"},"nextItem":{"title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Delaying Jobs","permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-job-delay"}},"content":"A few weeks after fixing our delayed-job processor, one queue started behaving badly over the weekend.\\n\\nMonitoring caught it. At first it looked recoverable. By Tuesday it was clear it was not. A newly onboarded large customer was affected, which made the issue impossible to ignore.\\n\\nI got pulled into the investigation early because I had worked on that part of the backend before.\\n\\nThe incident pointed to a deeper design flaw: we were using Redis as a payload store, not as a coordination layer. This post is about why that distinction matters and how we fixed it.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## The incident\\n\\nAfter a few hours, we found the root cause.\\n\\nOur long-polling mechanism had entered a hot loop on one queue. Jobs were being retried and delayed over and over, so that queue never drained. Because the draining process was still too coupled to the rest of the system, one pathological queue slowed down others too.\\n\\nWe shipped a short-term fix quickly: stop retrying after `N` attempts and break the loop.\\n\\nThat solved the incident.\\n\\nIt did not solve the design.\\n\\n## The real problem\\n\\nThe original delayed-job storage put the full serialized job directly into a Redis sorted set.\\n\\nThat was convenient, but it created two serious problems:\\n\\n1. Redis memory usage scaled with payload size.\\n   Large jobs meant large sorted sets.\\n\\n2. A single backlog could get very expensive.\\n   We were using a large ElastiCache instance mainly to absorb spikes and pathological cases.\\n\\nAt the time, our delayed-job footprint had grown into the hundreds of gigabytes. That is a very expensive way to keep postponed work around.\\n\\nThe root cause was the same in both cases: Redis was holding full application data when it should have been holding only enough information to coordinate re-enqueueing.\\n\\n![delayed-jobs-old-design](/assets/delayed-jobs-old-design.excalidraw.light.svg#light)\\n![delayed-jobs-old-design](/assets/delayed-jobs-old-design.excalidraw.dark.svg#dark)\\n\\n### How to know if this applies to you\\n\\nLook at your Redis memory usage. If your delayed-job sorted sets consume a large share of total memory, or if your Redis instance size is driven by job payload size rather than queue count, you are likely storing too much application data in Redis.\\n\\n## The redesign\\n\\nThe principle was simple: Redis should store ordering and coordination data, not full delayed-job payloads.\\n\\nSo instead of treating Redis as the system of record for every postponed message, we introduced a storage abstraction with multiple backends. Redis stayed in the hot path, but it no longer carried the full job body in every case.\\n\\n![redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference-new-design-read](/assets/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference-new-design-read.excalidraw.light.svg#light)\\n![redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference-new-design-read](/assets/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference-new-design-read.excalidraw.dark.svg#dark)\\n\\n### New storage strategy\\n\\nThe storage decision depends on a few factors:\\n\\n- how long the delay will be\\n- how large the payload is\\n- whether a backend is enabled for that queue or tenant\\n- whether the preferred backend is available\\n\\nFor short delays or small payloads, Redis can still hold the full object.\\n\\nFor longer delays or larger payloads, the job body goes somewhere cheaper, such as S3, and Redis stores only a compact reference.\\n\\nA delayed-job member might look like this:\\n\\n```text\\ns3::some-queue::384192393192::<generated-uuid>\\n```\\n\\nThe prefix tells the processor which backend to use later. In this case, it fetches the payload through the `s3` storage implementation before re-enqueueing the job.\\n\\n### Practical migration path\\n\\nYou do not need to move everything at once.\\n\\n1. Start by adding the storage abstraction and keeping Redis as the default.\\n2. Route one queue or one tenant to the new backend.\\n3. Measure latency impact and failure modes.\\n4. Expand gradually.\\n\\nThe key is making the reference format self-describing so the processor does not need external configuration to know where to look.\\n\\n## Supporting changes\\n\\nWe also changed the delayed-job processing model itself. Each change supported the same principle: Redis coordinates, other systems store.\\n\\n### Decoupled from the scheduler\\n\\nThe delayed-job service now drives itself on an interval instead of depending on another scheduler component. That removes an unnecessary coupling that could block draining.\\n\\n### Circuit breaking\\n\\nWe added limits so a bad retry pattern cannot trap the processor forever in one hot loop. This prevents one queue from monopolizing the coordination layer.\\n\\n### Concurrent queue processing\\n\\nInstead of serializing too much work, we process multiple target queues concurrently with explicit limits. That improves draining speed while keeping resource usage controlled.\\n\\n### Better visibility\\n\\nWe added metrics for:\\n\\n- re-enqueue latency\\n- success and failure counts\\n- number of delayed jobs processed\\n- queue-level behavior over time\\n\\nDelayed-job systems often fail quietly until they fail loudly. Visibility is part of making the coordination layer operable.\\n\\n### Horizontal scaling\\n\\nBy changing how we pop work from Redis, we could run multiple delayed-job processors with a cleaner coordination model than before.\\n\\nThat made the system more resilient under abnormal load.\\n\\n## Expected impact\\n\\nThe biggest expected win was infrastructure size.\\n\\nIf Redis stores compact references instead of large payloads for long-lived delayed jobs, memory usage drops dramatically. In our case, the difference was large enough to justify the redesign by itself.\\n\\nThe broader goals were:\\n\\n- much smaller Redis memory usage\\n- faster draining under stress\\n- less coupling between queues and backend components\\n- better support for horizontal scaling\\n- clearer operational visibility\\n\\n## Remaining concerns\\n\\nNo redesign removes all trade-offs. The important questions after the change were:\\n\\n- how many delayed jobs per second can we sustain?\\n- what do p75, p90, and p99 latencies look like?\\n- how much will S3 fetch latency affect re-enqueue speed?\\n- how low can we safely size Redis now?\\n- what happens if Redis itself becomes unavailable?\\n\\nThose are much healthier questions than \\"why is this one queue consuming hundreds of gigabytes of memory?\\"\\n\\n## Takeaway\\n\\nRedis is extremely useful for coordination and ordering, but that does not mean it should hold every byte of every object forever.\\n\\nThe best Redis designs often store less application data and more control-plane data.\\n\\nIn our case, moving from full payloads to references turned Redis from an expensive payload warehouse into a fast coordination layer.\\n\\n### When to consider this pattern\\n\\nConsider moving payloads out of Redis when:\\n\\n- your Redis memory is dominated by job bodies, not queue metadata\\n- you have jobs delayed for minutes or hours with large payloads\\n- your Redis instance size is driven by peak backlog, not steady-state load\\n- you already have cheap object storage available"},{"id":"/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-job-delay","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-job-delay","source":"@site/blog/2024-03-15/redis-is-more-than-cache-job-delay.mdx","title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Delaying Jobs","description":"How we used Redis sorted sets to delay and retry jobs, and why the consumption pattern matters more than the data structure.","date":"2024-03-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"redis","permalink":"/blog/tags/redis"},{"inline":true,"label":"jobs","permalink":"/blog/tags/jobs"},{"inline":true,"label":"pubsub","permalink":"/blog/tags/pubsub"},{"inline":true,"label":"readisismorethanacache","permalink":"/blog/tags/readisismorethanacache"}],"readingTime":4.34,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Delaying Jobs","description":"How we used Redis sorted sets to delay and retry jobs, and why the consumption pattern matters more than the data structure.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["redis","jobs","pubsub","readisismorethanacache"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Data Reference","permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-data-reference"},"nextItem":{"title":"The Zalgo Effect and Resource Leakage","permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/zalgo-effect-resource-leakage"}},"content":"At Luma Health, our backend ran on RabbitMQ and async jobs. Delayed execution was not an edge case. It was a core feature.\\n\\nA job might need to wait because an external system was down. Or it might just need a retry in five seconds. Either way, we needed a place to hold work until it was time to publish it again.\\n\\nRedis seemed perfect. Our first design was simple. It also fell apart under load.\\n\\nThe lesson of this post is that the access pattern matters as much as the data structure choice.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## The original design\\n\\nWhen a handler wanted to postpone a job, we serialized the job as JSON and stored it in a Redis sorted set. The score was the retry timestamp.\\n\\nEvery five seconds, a scheduled process would:\\n\\n1. read the set of delayed-job queues\\n2. fetch ready jobs with `ZRANGEBYSCORE`\\n3. publish them back to RabbitMQ\\n4. remove them from the sorted set\\n\\nIt was easy to explain. It was also easy to break.\\n\\n## Where it failed\\n\\nThree problems kept getting worse:\\n\\n1. It could not catch up with large backlogs.\\n   We fetched jobs in chunks, so a fast-growing queue could stay behind indefinitely.\\n\\n2. It used too much memory.\\n   Large batches were loaded into memory before being removed.\\n\\n3. It was awkward to scale horizontally.\\n   The fetch-then-delete model made multi-consumer coordination harder than it needed to be.\\n\\nAt its worst, the system pushed Redis memory usage toward tens of gigabytes and still struggled to drain delayed work.\\n\\nAll three problems had the same root cause: we were reading work in large batches and deleting it separately.\\n\\n### How to know if you have the same problem\\n\\nCheck whether your service:\\n- fetches batches but sometimes fails to delete them atomically\\n- grows in memory as the backlog grows\\n- cannot safely run multiple instances\\n- hits a throughput ceiling regardless of resources\\n\\nIf any of those sound familiar, the consumption pattern is likely the bottleneck, not Redis itself.\\n\\n## The change that mattered\\n\\nWe kept the same Redis data structure and changed only how we consumed it.\\n\\nInstead of fetching large batches into memory, we moved to a streaming-style approach:\\n\\n1. estimate ready jobs with `ZCOUNT`\\n2. create an async iterator\\n3. consume jobs one by one with `ZPOPMIN`\\n4. publish each job as it is popped\\n\\nThe key change was switching from fetch-then-delete to pop-as-you-go.\\n\\n`ZPOPMIN` worked well because it removes the lowest-score item as part of the read.\\n\\nSo instead of:\\n\\n- read a large batch\\n- keep it in memory\\n- publish it\\n- delete it later\\n\\nwe now had:\\n\\n- pop one ready job\\n- publish it\\n- move on\\n\\n![process-delayed-jobs-code](/assets/process-delayed-jobs-code.webp)\\n\\n## Why this was better\\n\\n### Lower memory pressure\\n\\nWe stopped pulling large delayed-job batches into memory, so the process became much more stable.\\n\\n### Better backlog behavior\\n\\nThroughput was still limited by Redis and publish speed, but the processor no longer paid the same large batch cost up front.\\n\\n### Easier scaling\\n\\nUsing destructive reads made coordination simpler than the previous model.\\n\\nIt did not solve every distributed-systems problem, but it gave us a much better base.\\n\\n## Results\\n\\nThe results were better than the size of the code change suggested.\\n\\n- we drained a backlog that had grown to roughly 40 GB\\n- process memory dropped from multi-gigabyte levels to a few hundred megabytes\\n- Redis sizing pressure fell enough to affect infrastructure cost\\n\\nThis was one of those cases where the win came from using the same data structure in a better way.\\n\\n![aws-memory-consumption](/assets/aws-memory-consumption.webp)\\n\\n![memory-delayed-jobs](/assets/memory-delayed-jobs.webp)\\n\\n![git-diff-memory-delayed-jobs](/assets/git-diff-memory-delayed-jobs.webp)\\n\\n## The broader point\\n\\nThis is why I like saying Redis is more than a cache.\\n\\nA sorted set is not just a place to store temporary values. With the right access pattern, it can act as a lightweight time-ordered work queue.\\n\\nThe hard part is usually not picking Redis. It is picking a consumption pattern that still works once the backlog stops being small.\\n\\n## Takeaways\\n\\n- Redis sorted sets are a practical building block for delayed jobs.\\n- Consumption strategy matters as much as data structure choice.\\n- Streaming-style consumption ages better than loading big batches into memory.\\n- A small algorithmic change can remove both cost and reliability problems.\\n\\n## What to check in your own system\\n\\nIf you already use Redis for delayed jobs:\\n\\n1. Are you fetching and then deleting, or removing as you read?\\n2. Does your processor memory grow with backlog size?\\n3. Can you safely run more than one consumer?\\n4. Do you have visibility into queue depth, processing lag, and consumer health?\\n\\nIf the answer to any of those questions concerns you, the fix may be simpler than replacing Redis.\\n\\n## Final thought\\n\\nThere are many ways to implement delayed jobs. RabbitMQ plugins, dedicated schedulers, and other persistence layers are all fair options.\\n\\nBut in day-to-day engineering, the best improvement is often the one that solves the current problem with the least operational drama.\\n\\nIn our case, that meant keeping Redis and fixing how we consumed it."},{"id":"/2024/03/15/zalgo-effect-resource-leakage","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/zalgo-effect-resource-leakage","source":"@site/blog/2024-03-15/zalgo-effect-resource-leakage.mdx","title":"The Zalgo Effect and Resource Leakage","description":"How mixing sync and async code in NodeJS caused RabbitMQ channel exhaustion in production, and why caching the promise instead of the result fixes it.","date":"2024-03-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"nodejs","permalink":"/blog/tags/nodejs"},{"inline":true,"label":"zalgo-effect","permalink":"/blog/tags/zalgo-effect"}],"readingTime":3.97,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"The Zalgo Effect and Resource Leakage","description":"How mixing sync and async code in NodeJS caused RabbitMQ channel exhaustion in production, and why caching the promise instead of the result fixes it.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["nodejs","zalgo-effect"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Redis is More Than a Cache - Delaying Jobs","permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/redis-is-more-than-cache-job-delay"},"nextItem":{"title":"NodeJS 101 - Lazy Initialization","permalink":"/blog/2023/12/24/nodejs-101-lazy-init"}},"content":"In JavaScript, Zalgo usually refers to APIs that behave synchronously in some paths and asynchronously in others.\\n\\nIn practice, you see the same kind of bug when sync-looking control flow is mixed with async initialization and timing becomes part of correctness.\\n\\nYou may not notice it in a toy example, but you absolutely notice it in production.\\n\\nThis post is about one specific variant: lazy initialization that races with itself under concurrency, and the single change that fixes it.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## The incident\\n\\nOne day our SRE team started receiving PagerDuty alerts from services that were repeatedly restarting with errors like:\\n\\n```text\\nError: No channels left to allocate\\n```\\n\\nThe affected services used RabbitMQ. Channel allocation was being exhausted, which meant something was creating channels and not reusing them properly.\\n\\nThe failing service mostly fanned out messages to many other services. At first glance, that should have been simple: create a queue abstraction, publish concurrently, move on.\\n\\nBut RabbitMQ management showed that the connection had accumulated far more channels than expected.\\n\\nSomething was leaking.\\n\\n## Why it only happened sometimes\\n\\nThat was the clue.\\n\\nIf a resource leak appears only under certain timing conditions, the bug often lives in initialization or concurrency rather than in a simple missing cleanup call.\\n\\nOur messaging abstraction dated back to the Node 4 era, when callback-style code was still the default. It had grown around that model for years.\\n\\nThe queue abstraction had two channel concepts:\\n\\n1. a consume channel, created during connection setup\\n2. a confirm channel, created lazily when publishing\\n\\nThe problem lived in the second one.\\n\\n## The bug pattern\\n\\nThe publish path roughly did this:\\n\\n1. check whether `confirmChannel` already exists\\n2. if it does, return it\\n3. if it does not, create it asynchronously and assign it later\\n\\nThat seems harmless until two concurrent publish operations hit the same check before the first initialization finishes.\\n\\nIn that window:\\n\\n- request A sees no channel and starts creating one\\n- request B also sees no channel and starts creating one\\n- both channels are created\\n- the last assignment wins\\n- the earlier channel stays open but is no longer referenced\\n\\nThat is the leak.\\n\\nNot because RabbitMQ was strange, but because our lazy initialization was racing with itself.\\n\\n### How to spot this in your own code\\n\\nLook for patterns like this:\\n\\n```javascript\\nif (!this.resource) {\\n  this.resource = await createResource();\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIf that check runs concurrently, you have the same race condition. The fix is to cache the promise, not the result.\\n\\n## Why this is Zalgo-shaped\\n\\nThe core problem was that resource existence was checked synchronously while resource creation finished asynchronously.\\n\\nThat made the correctness of the code depend on timing.\\n\\nWhenever timing becomes part of the contract by accident, Zalgo is usually nearby.\\n\\n## The fix\\n\\nThe first fix we shipped was conservative: initialize the channel once, await it, and only then fan out the publish operations.\\n\\nThat was the lowest-risk change.\\n\\nThe more robust long-term fix is a standard pattern:\\n\\n- store the initialization promise itself\\n- return the same promise to all concurrent callers\\n- replace or clear it if initialization fails and must be retried\\n\\nIn other words, do this:\\n\\n```javascript\\nclass Queue {\\n  constructor(connection) {\\n    this.connection = connection;\\n    this.confirmChannelPromise = null;\\n  }\\n\\n  getConfirmChannel() {\\n    if (!this.confirmChannelPromise) {\\n      this.confirmChannelPromise = this.connection.createConfirmChannel();\\n    }\\n\\n    return this.confirmChannelPromise;\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nNow the first caller starts creation, and every concurrent caller awaits the same promise.\\n\\nNo duplicate channels.\\nNo orphaned resources.\\nNo timing-dependent correctness.\\n\\n## Why this works\\n\\nThe important detail is that assigning the promise is synchronous.\\n\\nThe async work still happens later, but the decision that initialization is already in progress happens immediately in the same synchronous execution block.\\n\\nThat gives you one shared future instead of several competing initializations.\\n\\n## The core lesson\\n\\nWhen lazily initializing async resources in NodeJS, do not cache only the resolved resource.\\n\\nCache the promise.\\n\\nThat one detail is the difference between:\\n\\n- one initialization\\n- and several expensive, leaking, racing initializations\\n\\n### When this pattern does not apply\\n\\nDo not use promise caching when:\\n- the resource must be recreated after every failure\\n- initialization is intentionally retried with different parameters\\n- you need to force re-initialization on every call for testing\\n\\nIn those cases, use explicit initialization or a factory instead.\\n\\n## Final thought\\n\\nA lot of old NodeJS systems carry abstractions built in a callback-first world and then gradually adapted to promises.\\n\\nThat is exactly where bugs like this tend to hide.\\n\\nIf a resource is created lazily and accessed concurrently, inspect the initialization path carefully. If the code checks synchronously and assigns asynchronously, you may already have a leak waiting for traffic.\\n\\n### Quick code-review checklist\\n\\n- [ ] Lazy initialization happens in a concurrent path\\n- [ ] The existence check is synchronous but the creation is async\\n- [ ] The result is cached but the promise is not\\n- [ ] There is no retry or failure cleanup logic"},{"id":"/2023/12/24/nodejs-101-lazy-init","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2023/12/24/nodejs-101-lazy-init","source":"@site/blog/2023-12-24/nodejs-101-lazy-init.mdx","title":"NodeJS 101 - Lazy Initialization","description":"Two practical patterns for async resource initialization in NodeJS, and how to choose between them.","date":"2023-12-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"nodejs","permalink":"/blog/tags/nodejs"},{"inline":true,"label":"lazyinitialization","permalink":"/blog/tags/lazyinitialization"},{"inline":true,"label":"nodejs101","permalink":"/blog/tags/nodejs-101"},{"inline":true,"label":"node","permalink":"/blog/tags/node"}],"readingTime":3.19,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Lucas Weis Polesello","title":"donquixote engineering","url":"https://github.com/lukas8219","email":"lucas.polesello@lwpsoftwares.com","socials":{"x":"https://x.com/luucaspole"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/lukas8219.png","key":"lukas8219","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"NodeJS 101 - Lazy Initialization","description":"Two practical patterns for async resource initialization in NodeJS, and how to choose between them.","authors":"lukas8219","tags":["nodejs","lazyinitialization","nodejs101","node"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"The Zalgo Effect and Resource Leakage","permalink":"/blog/2024/03/15/zalgo-effect-resource-leakage"}},"content":"Here is a small problem that never looks hard until it bites you.\\n\\nYou build a class that needs a database connection. The constructor runs, but the connection is not ready yet. Someone calls a method. It fails.\\n\\nThe core question is not how to connect. It is how to model the lifecycle so the caller knows when the resource is safe to use.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\nThese are the two patterns I reach for. The post is about when each one fits, and why I prefer the first.\\n\\n## 1. Explicit initialization\\n\\nThe simplest option is to make initialization part of the API.\\n\\nThe caller creates the object, then calls `connect()` before using it.\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst redis = require(\'redis\');\\nconst crypto = require(\'crypto\');\\n\\nclass DistributedDataStructure {\\n  constructor() {\\n    this.client = redis.createClient();\\n  }\\n\\n  async connect() {\\n    await this.client.connect();\\n  }\\n\\n  async add(staffName, reviewId) {\\n    const accountName = await this.client.get(staffName);\\n    return this.client.sAdd(`v1:${accountName}:pending-reviews`, reviewId);\\n  }\\n}\\n\\n(async () => {\\n  const ds = new DistributedDataStructure();\\n  await ds.connect();\\n  await ds.add(\'Jerome\', crypto.randomBytes(12).toString(\'hex\'));\\n})();\\n```\\n\\n### Why this works well\\n\\n- easy to understand\\n- initialization is explicit\\n- failures happen in one place\\n- very little hidden behavior\\n\\n### Trade-off\\n\\nThe caller must remember to call `connect()`.\\n\\nIn a small codebase, that may be fine. In a bigger or older one, someone will eventually forget.\\n\\n### How to spot the problem\\n\\nIf you see classes that throw connection errors on first method call, or tests that mysteriously fail unless run in a certain order, check whether initialization is explicit.\\n\\n## 2. Proxy-based lazy initialization\\n\\nSometimes you need to create the object in synchronous code, but you still want the first real method call to wait for setup.\\n\\nThat is where a `Proxy` can help.\\n\\nThe example below is a pattern sketch, not a canonical Redis recipe. The exact readiness signal depends on the client library.\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst redis = require(\'redis\');\\nconst { once } = require(\'events\');\\nconst crypto = require(\'crypto\');\\n\\nclass ProxiedDistributedDataStructure {\\n  constructor() {\\n    this.client = redis.createClient();\\n    this.client.connect();\\n\\n    return new Proxy(this, {\\n      get(target, property) {\\n        const value = target[property];\\n        if (typeof value !== \'function\') {\\n          return value;\\n        }\\n\\n        return async function (...args) {\\n          if (!target.client.isReady) {\\n            await once(target.client, \'ready\');\\n          }\\n          return value.apply(target, args);\\n        };\\n      },\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  async add(staffName, reviewId) {\\n    const accountName = await this.client.get(staffName);\\n    return this.client.sAdd(`v1:${accountName}:pending-reviews`, reviewId);\\n  }\\n}\\n\\n(async () => {\\n  const ds = new ProxiedDistributedDataStructure();\\n  await ds.add(\'Jerome\', crypto.randomBytes(12).toString(\'hex\'));\\n})();\\n```\\n\\n## When this helps\\n\\nUse this when:\\n\\n- the object must be created in synchronous code\\n- changing all callers is too expensive\\n- you are working with legacy initialization flows\\n- you want the first method call to absorb setup cost\\n\\n## Trade-offs\\n\\nThis is nicer for callers, but harder to reason about.\\n\\nA method call that looks immediate may now wait on hidden setup work.\\n\\nThat means:\\n\\n- debugging gets harder\\n- errors can show up later\\n- method wrapping needs care\\n- the abstraction is easier to break\\n\\n### A common mistake\\n\\nIf the initialization fails, the proxy will likely retry on every method call. Consider caching the promise itself and handling rejection explicitly, or adding a failed-state guard.\\n\\nSo while the Proxy approach is useful, I still treat it as the riskier tool.\\n\\n## The decision framework\\n\\nThe broader point is that async resource initialization is part of your API design, and the choice between patterns depends on who controls the caller.\\n\\nA simple heuristic:\\n\\n- use `connect()` when you own the callers and want a clear lifecycle\\n- use a `Proxy` when you cannot change the callers and compatibility matters more\\n- use a factory function when you can afford to make construction async\\n\\n## Final note\\n\\nSome client libraries already provide buffering or connection management that reduces the need for custom lazy wrappers.\\n\\nEither way, make the initialization contract explicit, or hide it very carefully.\\n\\n### Quick checklist\\n\\nBefore adding lazy initialization, ask:\\n\\n- [ ] Can I make the constructor caller async instead?\\n- [ ] Will the first-method-call latency surprise anyone?\\n- [ ] What happens if initialization fails?\\n- [ ] Can I test this without mocking the Proxy behavior?"}]}}')}}]);